<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en-US">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Earth Tweets</title>
  <%- css('style') %>
</head>
<body>

<div class="wrapper">
  <div id="container"></div>

  <div id="title">Earth Tweets</div>

  <div id="currentInfo">
    <p>This is a mashup of the Google Data Arts Team's WebGL Globe project and the Twitter Streaming API. Live data is piped in from Twitter to a Node.js server, then sent to the browser through a bidirectional WebSocket connection and mapped onto a three-dimensional map of the Earth in real time.</p>

    <p><strong>Click</strong> on the planet and <strong>drag around</strong>. Use <strong>mousewheel</strong> or <strong>up</strong> and <strong>down</strong> arrows to zoom.</p>

    <p><button id="toggle-stream" class="btn btn-inverse"><i class="icon-play icon-white"></i> Start streaming live data</button></p>
    <p><button id="toggle-panning" class="btn btn-inverse"><i class="icon-map-marker icon-white"></i> Stop panning to tweets</button></p>
  </div>

  <div id="info">Based on <strong><a href="http://www.chromeexperiments.com/globe" target="_blank">WebGL Globe</a></strong> by the Google Data Arts Team <span class="bull">&bull;</span> Data acquired from <a href="https://dev.twitter.com/docs/streaming-apis" target="_blank">Twitter Streaming API</a></div>
</div>

<script src="/socket.io/socket.io.js"></script>
<script src="http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?sensor=false"></script>
<%- js('client') %>

</body>
</html>
